\subsection{Two pole structure of the $\Lambda(1405)$}

In the 2000's, the Chiral unitary model suggested that "$\Lambda(1405)$" is the dynamically generated state that is contributed from two poles,
one is the resonant pole of $\pi\Sigma$ and the other is the pole of $\bar{K}N$ bound state that is located below the threshold\cite{Jido}.
According to this theory, the pole position of the $\bar{K}N$ appears nearer the $\bar{K}N$ threshold than $\Lambda(1405)$ mass as Fig\ref{fig:Jido}.
Lattice QCD simulation by the HAL collaboration reported that the $\Lambda(1405)$ is the molecular state that is $\bar{K}N$ bound state dominant\cite{HalQCD} as shown in Fit\ref{fig:Hall}.

