Some photoproductions of the $\Lambda(1405)$ was performed.
The first photoproduction of $\Lambda(1405)$ was performed at LEPS\cite{Niiyama}.
They irradiated $1.5\sim2.4GeV$ $\gamma$ beam on the proton target and measured $\gamma p \rightarrow K^+ Y^*$ production with $K^+$ angle is $0.8<\cos\theta_{K^+}<1.0$ at the center of mass.
They reported a difference of $\pi^+\Sigma^-$ and $\pi^-\Sigma^+$ spectra as Fig\ref{fig:LEPS_L1405} which means the existence of the interference term between $I=0$ and $I=1$ channel.
The CLAS collaboration experimented same reaction employed polarized $\gamma$ beam with $2.55<W<2.85 GeV$ and measured $K^+$ of $0.6<\cos\theta<0.9$.
They experimentally concluded the spin-parity of $\Lambda(1405)$ is $J^P=\frac{1}{2}^-$\cite{CLAS}.

The $\Lambda(1405)$ production using $pp\rightarrow (\pi^{\pm}\Sigma^{\pm})p K^+$ was reported by the HADES\cite{HADES_L1405}, in which $\Lambda(1405)$ peak position was observed below $1.4GeV$.
The possibility that this result comes from the $\pi\Sigma$ pole was discussed by \cite{Fabbietti}. 
Although the measurement $\Lambda(1405)$ employed various reaction was performed, it's structure have been controversial.

